item.title: Australian Reporters Flee China After Late-Night Visits From State Security
item.description: The evacuation of two Australian journalists from China after visits and interviews with Chinese security officials has set off alarms at a nerve-racking time for foreign press in the country.

item.title: Ship With 27 Migrants Locked in Limbo for More Than a Month
item.description: A commercial tanker has been anchored in the Mediterranean Sea with 27 rescued African migrants aboard for more than a month, caught in a stalemate as ports in the region refuse to allow the Maersk Etienne to dock.

item.title: Tokyo Olympics Can Coexist With Covid-19, Organizers Say
item.description: Japan’s Olympics minister said the country was determined to go ahead with the Summer Games next year despite some skepticism about whether athletes from around the world can safely participate in Tokyo.

item.title: Johnson Wants Scope to Boost Government Intervention, Rattling Brexit Talks
item.description: Trade negotiations that will define the future relationship between the U.K. and the European Union have stalled, in large part because Prime Minister Boris Johnson’s government wants the freedom to ignore EU rules limiting government subsidies of private companies.

item.title: Belarusian Protest Leader Ripped Up Passport to Avoid Expulsion, Supporters Say
item.description: Maria Kalesnikava, one of the last core opposition leaders left in Belarus, was detained at the border with Ukraine after thwarting an attempt to expel her from the country, Ukrainian authorities and her supporters said.

item.title: U.S. Military Is Offered New Bases in the Pacific
item.description: The Republic of Palau has asked the Pentagon to build ports, bases and airfields on the island nation, officials said, offering a boost to U.S. military expansion plans in Asia, as Washington aims to counter China.
